## Test Anti-Pattern Audit: `ProductCatalogTests.cs`

### Summary

| Severity | Count |
|----------|-------|
| **Critical** | 6 |
| **High** | 0 |
| **Medium** | 2 |
| **Low** | 1 |

This is a textbook **coverage-touching** test class. Every public method on `ProductCatalog` is called (achieving high line coverage), but almost nothing is actually verified. These tests will pass even if the production code is completely broken—they only fail on unhandled exceptions.

---

### 🔴 Critical Findings

#### 1. Coverage Touching (Systemic)

The entire class follows the pattern: call a method, skip assertions. 6 of 10 tests have **zero assertions**; the remaining 4 use only `Assert.IsNotNull` which proves almost nothing (a method returning an empty list or wrong data still passes).

#### 2. No Assertions — `AddProduct_Works` (line 17)

```csharp
// BEFORE — proves nothing
_catalog.AddProduct(product);

// AFTER — verify the product was stored
_catalog.AddProduct(product);
var retrieved = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.AreEqual("Widget", retrieved?.Name);
Assert.AreEqual(9.99m, retrieved?.Price);
```

#### 3. No Assertions — `UpdatePrice_Works` (line 32)

```csharp
// BEFORE — price might not change at all
_catalog.UpdatePrice("SKU-001", 14.99m);

// AFTER — verify the new price
_catalog.UpdatePrice("SKU-001", 14.99m);
var updated = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.AreEqual(14.99m, updated?.Price);
```

#### 4. No Assertions — `RemoveProduct_Works` (line 39)

```csharp
// BEFORE — product might still exist
_catalog.RemoveProduct("SKU-001");

// AFTER — verify removal
_catalog.RemoveProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.IsNull(_catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001"));
```

#### 5. No Assertions — `GetProductCount_Works` (line 63)

```csharp
// BEFORE — result is discarded
var count = _catalog.GetProductCount();

// AFTER — verify count reflects state
_catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));
var count = _catalog.GetProductCount();
Assert.AreEqual(1, count);
```

#### 6. No Assertions — `ApplyBulkDiscount_Works` (line 69)

This is the most dangerous gap—`ApplyBulkDiscount` has real arithmetic logic (`Price * (1 - fraction)`) that could easily regress.

```csharp
// BEFORE — discount math is never checked
_catalog.ApplyBulkDiscount(0.10m);

// AFTER — verify prices are reduced correctly
_catalog.ApplyBulkDiscount(0.10m);
Assert.AreEqual(8.991m, _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001")?.Price);
Assert.AreEqual(17.991m, _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-002")?.Price);
```

